30 ARTICLE 44. FIRE SUPPRESSION EQUIPMENT
31 PROFESSIONALS
32 Chapter 1. Definitions
33 Sec. 1. The definitions in this chapter apply throughout this
34 article.
35 Sec. 2. "Board" refers to the board of firefighting personnel
36 standards and education established by IC 22-12-3-1.
37 Sec. 3. "Business license" refers to the following:
38 (1) A Class A business license described in IC 25-44-3-1.
39 (2) A Class B business license described in IC 25-44-3-1.
40 (3) A Class C business license described in IC 25-44-3-1.
41 (4) A Class D business license described in IC 25-44-3-1.
42 Sec. 4. "Carbon dioxide based engineered system" means a fire
2026 IN 1236—LS 6915/DI 153

3
1 suppression system that:
2 (1) requires individual calculations and design;
3 (2) uses components that are approved or recognized by a
4 nationally significant testing laboratory, as determined by the
5 board, for use in an engineered fire suppression system; and
6 (3) uses carbon dioxide as an extinguishing agent.
7 Sec. 5. "Carbon dioxide based fire extinguisher" means a
8 portable unit:
9 (1) designed to be used by a single person to fight a small,
10 localized fire; and
11 (2) that uses carbon dioxide as an extinguishing agent.
12 Sec. 6. "Carbon dioxide based preengineered system" means a
13 fire suppression system that:
14 (1) is designed and tested by a manufacturer to be a fixed
15 system;
16 (2) has predetermined:
17 (A) pipe sizes, lengths, and fittings; and
18 (B) nozzle types and numbers;
19 (3) is approved or recognized by a nationally significant
20 testing laboratory, as determined by the board, based on
21 actual fire tests; and
22 (4) uses carbon dioxide as an extinguishing agent.
23 Sec. 7. "Engineered system" means a fire suppression system
24 that:
25 (1) requires individual calculations and design;
26 (2) uses components that are approved or recognized by a
27 nationally significant testing laboratory, as determined by the
28 board, for use in an engineered fire suppression system; and
29 (3) does not use carbon dioxide as an extinguishing agent.
30 Sec. 8. "Fire extinguisher" means a portable unit:
31 (1) designed to be used by a single person to fight a small,
32 localized fire; and
33 (2) that does not use carbon dioxide as an extinguishing agent.
34 Sec. 9. "Preengineered system" means a fire suppression system
35 that:
36 (1) is designed and tested by a manufacturer to be a fixed
37 system;
38 (2) has predetermined:
39 (A) pipe sizes, lengths, and fittings; and
40 (B) nozzle types and numbers;
41 (3) is approved or recognized by a nationally significant
42 testing laboratory, as determined by the board, based on
2026 IN 1236—LS 6915/DI 153

4
1 actual fire tests; and
2 (4) does not use carbon dioxide as an extinguishing agent.
3 Sec. 10. "Technician license" refers to the following:
4 (1) A Class 1 technician license described in IC 25-44-4-1.
5 (2) A Class 2 technician license described in IC 25-44-4-1.
6 (3) A Class 3 technician license described in IC 25-44-4-1.
7 (4) A Class 4 technician license described in IC 25-44-4-1.
8 Chapter 2. Duties and Powers of the Board; Rulemaking
9 Sec. 1. (a) The board shall:
10 (1) enforce and administer this article;
11 (2) adopt rules under IC 4-22-2 for the administration and
12 enforcement of this article;
13 (3) establish standards for the competent practice of fire
14 suppression equipment professionals;
15 (4) issue, deny, suspend, and revoke licenses in accordance
16 with this article;
17 (5) subject to IC 4-21.5, IC 25-1-7, and IC 25-1-11, discipline
18 individuals who are licensed under this article for violations
19 of this article;
20 (6) establish fees in accordance with IC 25-1-8; and
21 (7) maintain appropriate records with respect to the
22 administration of this article.
23 (b) In establishing standards under subsection (a)(3), the board
24 shall consider the relevant standards of the National Fire
25 Protection Association. However, the standards adopted by the
26 board may not conflict with rules adopted under IC 22-13-2-2.
27 Sec. 2. (a) The board shall adopt rules concerning the continuing
28 education required for the renewal of licenses under this article.
29 (b) The rules must do the following:
30 (1) Establish procedures for approving organizations that
31 provide continuing education.
32 (2) Prescribe the content, duration, and organization of
33 continuing education courses that contribute to the general
34 competence of license holders.
35 Chapter 3. Business Licensing
36 Sec. 1. (a) A Class A business license authorizes a person to
37 engage in the business of:
38 (1) service;
39 (2) repair;
40 (3) recharging;
41 (4) inspection;
42 (5) installation; or
2026 IN 1236—LS 6915/DI 153

5
1 (6) maintenance;
2 with respect to fire extinguishers.
3 (b) A Class B business license authorizes a person to:
4 (1) engage in the business of:
5 (A) service;
6 (B) repair;
7 (C) recharging;
8 (D) inspection;
9 (E) installation;
10 (F) maintenance; or
11 (G) hydrostatic testing;
12 with respect to fire extinguishers; and
13 (2) engage in the business of recharging with respect to
14 carbon dioxide based fire extinguishers.
15 (c) A Class C business license authorizes a person to:
16 (1) engage in the business of:
17 (A) service;
18 (B) repair;
19 (C) recharging;
20 (D) inspection;
21 (E) installation;
22 (F) maintenance; or
23 (G) hydrostatic testing;
24 with respect to fire extinguishers and preengineered systems;
25 and
26 (2) engage in the business of recharging with respect to
27 carbon dioxide based fire extinguishers.
28 (d) A Class D business license authorizes a person to engage in
29 the business of:
30 (1) service;
31 (2) repair;
32 (3) recharging;
33 (4) inspection;
34 (5) installation;
35 (6) maintenance; or
36 (7) hydrostatic testing;
37 with respect to fire extinguishers, preengineered systems,
38 engineered systems, carbon dioxide based fire extinguishers,
39 carbon dioxide based preengineered systems, and carbon dioxide
40 based engineered systems.
41 Sec. 2. A person may not engage in the business of:
42 (1) service;
2026 IN 1236—LS 6915/DI 153

6
1 (2) repair;
2 (3) recharging;
3 (4) inspection;
4 (5) installation;
5 (6) maintenance; or
6 (7) hydrostatic testing;
7 with respect to fire extinguishers, preengineered systems,
8 engineered systems, carbon dioxide based fire extinguishers,
9 carbon dioxide based preengineered systems, or carbon dioxide
10 based engineered systems without first obtaining the appropriate
11 business license.
12 Sec. 3. A separate business license is required for each place of
13 business where the actions described in section 2 of this chapter
14 occur.
15 Sec. 4. (a) A business license only allows an individual to engage
16 in the activities authorized by the license class.
17 (b) A person holding a business license must follow all
18 applicable manufacturer's maintenance and installation
19 instructions with respect to preengineered systems, engineered
20 systems, carbon dioxide based preengineered systems, and carbon
21 dioxide based engineered systems.
22 Sec. 5. To be issued a business license, an individual must do the
23 following:
24 (1) Furnish evidence satisfactory to the board showing that
25 the individual:
26 (A) is at least eighteen (18) years of age;
27 (B) has:
28 (i) experience;
29 (ii) equipment; and
30 (iii) insurance;
31 commensurate with the class of business license sought;
32 (C) completed all training prescribed by the board; and
33 (D) received a passing score on an examination prescribed
34 or approved by the board.
35 (2) Submit to a national criminal history background check
36 under IC 25-1-1.1-4 and furnish satisfactory evidence to the
37 board that the individual has not been convicted of a crime
38 that has a direct bearing on the individual's ability to practice
39 competently.
40 (3) Apply for the business license in the manner prescribed by
41 the board.
42 (4) Pay a fee established by the board.
